d the black and queer communities with open arms; like many iconic discos, Catch One began as a place where marginalized groups could gather, without fear of exclusion or poor treatment.\r\n\r\nBy the end of this summer, the beloved venue will shut its doors to the public, one of many casualties of an ever-changing, gentrified and gentrifying Los Angeles.\r\n\r\nWhen popular culture caught on to the disco craze, Catch One <a href=\"http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/great-reads/la-et-c1-black-gay-clubs-20150316-story.html#page=2\">begun</a> to welcome guests from all walks of life and areas of the city, but remained a watering hole for its original demographic, maintaining its status as the last black-owned gay club in the city.\r\n\r\nThe venues importance spans beyond just music history, though clubs like Catch One grew to become hubs of information and support for black gay men during the HIV epidemic, as government agencies and health officials denied information to the African American community and general public.\r\n\r\n\"Having community space at the intersection of both gender, sexuality and race has been really important as a resource for navigating racism, homophobia and heterosexism,\" USC professor Shane\'a Thomas told the LA Times, explaining that spaces like Jewels Catch One werent just parties - they werevital forums for connection and acceptance to the communities they served, and were a place black gay men could congregateover a distinct &amp; specific shared experience that is too easily generalized in present day Los Angeles.\r\n\r\n\"We have to find a space to validate who we are,\" Thomas expanded. \"There\'s something about being around others like you, how great it feels to be affirmed in a place where people look like you.\"\r\n\r\nFor many Angelinos, Jewels Catch One was one of these crucial spaces - somewhere otherwise repressed iterations of sexuality and culture could be expressed freely, outside of the boundaries of consumer-driven pop and capitalist ethos.\r\n\r\nAs disco grew &amp; grows increasingly commercialized, repopularized, and commercialized once more, we tend to see the whitewashing and ultimate erasure of places like Jewels Catch One. Meanwhile, as Hollywood and West LA arefurther and further gentrified and night clubs like West Hollywoods <a href=\"http://www.yelp.com/biz/rage-west-hollywood-2\">Rage</a> emerge, many wonder about the role of spaces like Jewels Catch One and how their history canbe preserved.\r\n\r\nWhile the closure will certainly be tearful parting for many of us, if nothing else, it at least might signal the diffusion of once-isolated marginalized groups throughout LA\'s neighborhoods, or be symptomatic of slowly eroding taboos surrounding sexual expression, race, geography and culture.\r\n\r\nYou can stop by Jewels Catch One before the end of the summer to oogle the clubs eponynous mirror balls one last time, sip a farewell drink, and mourn one of LAs most beloved discos.\r\n\r\n<i>Walk the Night is your new best friend. Like Tinder without the bodily fluid exchange  we scour the web, pluck from pop cultures best and lowest hanging fruit, and stick out after hours til the last last-call. We walk the night hard  so you dont have to.</i>','Lights Out for Catch One','','publish','open','open','','lights-out-for-catch-one','','','2015-05-27 18:57:03','2015-05-27 18:57:03','',0,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?p=258',0,'post','',0),(259,5,'2015-05-27 01:15:00','2015-05-27 01:15:00','','Jewel\'s Catch One-7','Courtesy of Google ','inherit','open','open','','jewels-catch-one-7','','','2015-05-27 01:15:15','2015-05-27 01:15:15','',258,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Jewels-Catch-One-7.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(267,1,'2015-05-27 20:21:16','2015-05-27 20:21:16','<strong>Join our pride and get exclusive access to all Catnip Club events and products.</strong>\r\n\r\nMembers get:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Free entry to select events</li>\