inherit','open','open','','teddys','','','2015-06-03 21:32:05','2015-06-03 21:32:05','',5,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/teddys.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(447,4,'2015-06-03 21:32:08','2015-06-03 21:32:08','','Frolic Room','','inherit','open','open','','thefrolicroom','','','2015-06-10 20:22:09','2015-06-10 20:22:09','',5,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/thefrolicroom.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(448,4,'2015-06-03 21:32:11','2015-06-03 21:32:11','','The Pikey','','inherit','open','open','','thepinkey-bw','','','2015-06-03 23:11:06','2015-06-03 23:11:06','',5,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/thepinkey-bw.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(449,4,'2015-06-03 21:32:13','2015-06-03 21:32:13','','Short Stop','','inherit','open','open','','theshortstop-bw','','','2015-06-03 23:06:58','2015-06-03 23:06:58','',5,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/theshortstop-bw.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(450,4,'2015-06-03 21:32:17','2015-06-03 21:32:17','','tropicana','','inherit','open','open','','tropicana','','','2015-06-03 21:32:17','2015-06-03 21:32:17','',5,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/tropicana.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(451,4,'2015-06-03 21:32:53','2015-06-03 21:32:53','','Thirsty Crow','','inherit','open','open','','thirstycrow-bw','','','2015-06-03 22:35:59','2015-06-03 22:35:59','',5,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/thirstycrow-bw.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(453,3,'2015-06-03 21:55:37','2015-06-03 21:55:37','[vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]Hidden away in the burbs of Glendale, Complex is a dark, cozy nightclub that hosts Ground Control Karaoke and various house and techno parties. Boasting a Funktion-One sound system, visuals and sound are some of the clubs greatest strong suits, and some parties even feature live art via bluetooth.\r\n\r\nThough Complex might seem a little out of the way, the sound makes it worth the trip  the venue not only brings in techno and house fans who typically dont wander beyond the confines of LA proper, but also lures well-known international acts.\r\n\r\nComplex hosts both big shows and smaller, local parties  beloved nu-disco radio show THATS DECK hosted their first event there, drawing an impressive crowd of weeknight subterraneans.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nDrinkwise, Complex is unconventional for a nightclub of its kind  no PBRs here. Despite the low lighting and grungy underground vibe, the bar specializes in infused cocktails and craft beers; bartenders are friendly and knowledgeable, able to accommodate brewmeisters esoteric selections and guide the hop-shy toward interesting introductions to craft beer or drinks featuring whichever infusion is on tap.\r\n\r\nOur beer novices recommend the Coopers Sparkling Ale, which is light and refreshing, and a little bitter, but not too much - weve found its perfect for sipping your way through long, sweltering LA nights and pulsing beats. Cocktails arent great, so we recommend splurging or keeping it simple with beer, cider or a shot.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nNestled around the corner, the outdoor smoking area is small but accommodating. A patio-style layout and picnic tables make it a great place to chat and meet people, a rare find in LA nightlife.\r\n\r\nThough street parking isnt unfathomable, we recommend taking an Uber or Lyft so you can fully enjoy the drink samplings.\r\n\r\n<b>The Lowdown</b>\r\n\r\nComplex is a Glendale venue offering a mixture of lively club nights, international DJ sets and Ground Control Karaoke. With a Funktion-One sound system, parties draw big European acts as well as local favorites. The bar specializes in craft beer and has unique brews for brewmeisters and habitually gluten-weary Angelenos alike.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text css_animation=\"\"][templatera id=\"349\"][/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Complex','','publish','open','open','','complexla','','','2015-08-12 18:29:27','2015-08-13 01:29:27','',201,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?page_id=453',0,'page','',0),(459,1,'2015-06-03 22:25:35','2015-06-03 22:25:35','','Order &ndash; June 3, 2015 @ 10:25 PM','','wc-processing','open','closed','order_556f7edc357eb','order-jun-03-2015-1025-pm','','','2015-06-03 22:25:35','2015-06-03 22:25:35','',0,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?post_type=shop_order&#038;p=459',0,'shop_order','',3),(463,3,'2015-06-03 22:36:19','2015-06-03 22:36:19','[vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]Born from an Aesop fable about a perishing crow desperate for a drink, the Thirsty Crow provides a watering hole where its a little easier to wet your whistle. This spirited bar sells over 100 whiskeys as well as 60+ bourbons.\r\n\r\nOrganic, soy, nonfat Angelenos, youre in luck! On top of selling an array of unique, seasonal drinks, the Thirsty Crow uses fresh-squeezed juice, makes their infusions in-house, and uses homemade shrubs, sherbets, jams, etc.\r\n\r\nThe bar is a bit pricey but you definitely get what you pay for. The head bartender, Cooper Gillespie, is known for his amazingly unique hand-crafted seasonal cocktails. If you find yourself in Silverlake in the Fall, you can enjoy a Jack-Skellington-themed drink fit for any Pumpkin King or Queen.\r\n\r\nAround the corner, you can chow down on what is arguably the best ramen on Sunset at Silverlake Ramen. Just make sure to put your name down for ramen before going into the bar because it takes about a lifetime and a half to be seated. Further down the street, you can find one of LA\'s most unique Mexican restaurants, Diablos. Known for its delicious twist on Mexican cuisine, tasty sangrias, and a plethora of board games to play while you wait for your food, it\'s definitely worth the tipsy stumble down Sunset.\r\n\r\nIf youre seeking entertainment, come by the Thirsty Crow on Whiskey Wednesdays for $5 whiskeys or grab of group of friends for live jazz on Sundays. No matter when you go, however, you\'re bound to be around a large crowd full of different LA denizens any time of the week.\r\n\r\nThe bar offers a dark, mysterious speakeasy vibe, but it can be a tad too dark for comfort. You may have to whip out your phone or grab the nearest candle in order to read the cocktail menu. At the very least, the air is pungent with enough citrus and herbs to make you forget any temporary bar-blindness.\r\n\r\nThough service can take a minute, the more you smile and joke with the bartenders, the more they take care of you, so try channeling the Cheers bar if youre getting impatient.\r\n\r\n<b>The Lowdown</b>\r\n\r\nthe Thirsty Crow is a lovely hole-in-the-wall to grab a drink in Silverlake. The prices leave something to be desired, but nothing you wouldnt expect for the neighborhood. As spotty as the service can get, the drinks are made with fresh in-house ingredients and are definitely worth the wait. Most of all, the Thirsty Crow is the perfect place to take whiskey-loving Angelenos.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text css_animation=\"\"][templatera id=\"349\"][/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Thirsty Crow','','publish','open','open','','thirstycrowbar','','','2015-08-12 18:28:38','2015-08-13 01:28:38','',201,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?page_id=463',0,'page','',0),(465,1,'2015-06-03 22:41:33','2015-06-03 22:41:33','','Order &ndash; June 3, 2015 @ 10:41 PM','','wc-processing','open','closed','order_556f829713c5c','order-jun-03-2015-1041-pm','','','2015-06-03 22:41:33','2015-06-03 22:41:33','',0,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?post_type=shop_order&#038;p=465',0,'shop_order','',3),(469,1,'2015-06-03 22:59:54','2015-06-03 22:59:54','','Order &ndash; June 3, 2015 @ 10:59 PM','ypu can leave them in the door step, there is a deck out front with blue flower pots if you get lost .','wc-cancelled','open','closed','order_556f86ea29936','order-jun-03-2015-1059-pm','','','2015-06-04 00:25:49','2015-06-04 00:25:49','',0,'https://walkthenight.wpengine.com/losangeles/?post_type=shop_order&#038;p=469',0,'shop_order','',1),(471,3,'2015-06-03 23:02:38','2015-06-03 23:02:38','[vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]Lodged in a commercial nook of Echo Park adjacent to American Apparel, Mohawk Bend is most known for its wide selection of over 70 craft beers, but has plenty to offer even if you arent a brew connoisseur  our favorite is the infused vodkas; we recommend garlic, if youre feeling adventurous.\r\n\r\nAdorned with an antique theater marquee, Mohawk Bend is a mixture of neighborhood eatery, Hollywood-adjacent cocktail lounge, and upscale beer bar. There are communal tables and smaller booths near the romantic indoor fireplace, which are popular among couples and groups.\r\n\r\nThough Mohawk Bend is most known for its beverages, the food is just as much of a draw  though its lauded for its indulgent vegan-friendly fare, there are also snacks like chorizo-wrapped dates and a dressed-up fried chicken sandwich for carnivores. Wood-oven-fired pizzas are a favorite among regulars, but if youre stumped, dont be shy about asking for help  staff will gladly help you navigate the beer list, pick an appetizer, or sort through the cocktail menu. Though food is delicious, it tends to be pricey  come with an empty stomach and a full wallet.\r\n\r\nDuring weekend brunch, a jazz band plays in the back, harkening back to Mohawk Bends early days as a Vaudeville theater.\r\n\r\nMohawk Bend is a particularly good choice for groups due to its wide selection of indoor and outdoor seating choices and far-reaching menu, which manages to accommodate everyone from the carefree Ill drink anything types to the most gluten-, meat-, grain-, or refined-sugar-free Angelenos among us.\r\n\r\nThough its a pleasant bar to stop by at any time of day, weve found it\'s at its best at around 6pm, when locals are catching up over after-work drinks and crowds are lively and upbeat but not overwhelming. If you feel like you really deserve a mid-week pat on the back, its also nice to stop by on a lunch break, when the place is mostly empty, but sip slowly  the craft cocktails can be deceptively potent.\r\n\r\n<b>The Lowdown</b>\r\n\r\nMohawk Bend is a friendly neighborhood beer bar, restaurant and cocktail lounge in a historic Vaudeville Theater. Libations are delicious, but dont come cheap  service and seating options are both top-notch though, so its worth stopping by: we recommend splitting one of the decadent appetizers, and sampling an infused vodka or one of the 72 craft beers on tap.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text css_animation=\"\"][templatera id=\"349\"][/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Mohawk Bend','','publish','open','open','','mohawkla','','','2015-08-12 18:41:53','2015-08-13 01:41:53','',201,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?page_id=471',0,'page','',0),(473,3,'2015-06-03 23:07:18','2015-06-03 23:07:18','[vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]Once a cop bar, The Short Stop is now a hip Echo Park dive with a laid-back vibe and lots of room to dance. Though the bar can be a whirlwind of mustaches and flannel, the atmosphere isnt pretentious, nor are bar staff  though it can take a minute to get served.\r\n\r\nIf you do manage to hail a bartender, try one of the drink specials, which often feature high-end ingredients like St. Germaine, champagne and Blood Orange San Pellegrino.\r\n\r\nHappy-hour crowds are a mixture of post-game Dodger fans, boho locals and twenty-somethings from all parts of LA. On a busy night, you can even catch a roving member of the cast of <i>Girls </i>holding court in the corner booth, but dont stare  this is Echo Park, not Hollywood.\r\n\r\nWhile weekdays cater more to afterwork drinks and cultivate a neighborhood bar sensibility, The Short Stop gets rowdier (and sweatier) on weekends, when there also tends to be a line after 10pm. There is a narrow, outdoor smoking area in the back of the bar, but it isnt too roomy and you cant bring drinks out.\r\n\r\nDJs aim to make you move, playing EDM, top 40, classic and contemporary R&amp;B, and classics. Though theres also an adjacent room with a pool table, The Short Stop is primarily a destination for those who want to grind or swivel their hips. As Madonna said, Only when I\'m dancing can I feel this free.\r\n\r\n<b>The Lowdown </b>\r\n\r\nThe Short Stop was once a big Dodgers post-game hangout, but the bar is trying to redefine itself to cater to an edgier, broader audience. On weekdays, it maintains the quiet dive ethos, but weekends revolve around the dance floor, which can be a little overwhelming if you are looking to grab a quiet drink with friends. Additionally, on weekends, there tend to be sizable lines after 10 or 11pm.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text css_animation=\"\"][templatera id=\"349\"][/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Short Stop','','publish','open','open','','theshortstopechopark','','','2015-08-12 18:42:52','2015-08-13 01:42:52','',201,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?page_id=473',0,'page','',0),(475,3,'2015-06-03 23:13:09','2015-06-03 23:13:09','[vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]The Pikey is an upscale pub on Sunset with a Union Jack theme and a spacious, skylit dining room.\r\n\r\nChef Ralph Johnson hails from New Yorks Spotted Pig, and is known for dishes featuring local free-range chicken and Sunday roasts that come with Yorkshire pudding. If youre feeling Scottish, theres haggis with neeps and tatties, as well as single-malt scotch.\r\n\r\nThe bars jukebox plays classic rock like The Doors, and drinks range from infused absinthe, a house specialty, to simpler fare like The Coach and Horses (an homage to the dive that once occupied this space for decades): a shot of bourbon with a can of PBR. While the main dining room can get cramped, there are also hidden rooms, one of which boasts an impressive collection of Maharaja portraits.\r\n\r\nOwners Jared Meisler and Sean MacPherson (Il Covo, Roger Room) draw inspiration from the bars divey past, but dress it up with iron chandeliers and other luxe lighting fixtures and furnishings. The Pikeys food, like its liquor, takes pub standbys up a notch and a price bracket  Marys Vinegar Chicken will run you close to twenty dollars, while a Worcestershire aioli-smothered burger can be enjoyed for a tenner. The Pikeys specialty is chips (fries), which come with entrees and Brit-inspired dipping sauces like salt and vinegar  or ketchup for non-Anglophiles.\r\n\r\nIf your wallet is on the light side, we recommend coming for the 4-6pm happy hour, when house cocktails, well drinks, and wines are discounted.\r\n\r\nBoozy singles and small groups flock to the Pikey for Christmas and Easter Day, while its hearty food pairings also make it a popular choice for brunch. If youre feeling salacious, you can order a Divine Brown: a whiskey and Dr. Pepper, named after Hugh Grants infamous mistress.\r\n\r\n<b>The Lowdown </b>\r\n\r\nThe Pikey is an upscale gastropub with British-inspired food, drink and dcor. Servers are friendly, while Sunset offers lots of nearby street parking. If you want the full experience, come for a Sunday roast or even Christmas Dinner.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text css_animation=\"\"][templatera id=\"349\"][/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','The Pikey','','publish','open','open','','thepikeyla','','','2015-08-12 18:43:28','2015-08-13 01:43:28','',201,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?page_id=475',0,'page','',0),(477,3,'2015-06-03 23:24:05','2015-06-03 23:24:05','[vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]Break Room 86 is the newest of The Line Hotels chic bars and restaurants, and the Houston Brothers most recent LA venture. Like Good Times at Davey Waynes and the spots that preceded it, Break Room 86 goes for a curated, edgy period ethos and is hidden so as to siphon off foot traffic.\r\n\r\nThis works a little differently in Koreatown than it does in Hollywood  while deterring drunk stragglers is a necessary and worthwhile goal in the tourist-swamped enclaves of Hollywood Boulevard and Sunset, much of the fun of going out in small communities that arent fully gentrified is finding bars that function as watering holes for those who live and work in the area  Break Room 86 is not this. It is, essentially, a trendy Hollywood bar transplanted into Koreatown.\r\n\r\nYou enter Break Room 86 through a back entrance, where a host greets and escorts guests through a vending machine door into the darkly lit lounge. The process is a little overwrought, and feels more awkwardly contrived than the entry point of Davey Waynes that presumably inspired it.\r\n\r\nBreak Room 86s biggest themed attraction is a selection of retro arcade games  though bathroom attendants also strongly encouraged my friend and I to go in together, which we took as a cheeky 80s throwback. There are private karaoke rooms behind the bars antique phone booth and wall of lockers, while neon signature drinks are fairly sugary, featuring rum and whiskey infusions, wine coolers, fruit syrups and liqueurs.\r\n\r\nDress is trendy, and though it\'s possible to get in without a reservation, we recommend making one  particularly on weekends.\r\n\r\n<b>The Lowdown </b>\r\n\r\nBreak Room 86 is the Houston Brothers (No Vacancy, Dirty Laundry, Good Times at Davey Waynes) newest bar, located in the basement of The Line Hotel in Koreatown. The bar has an 80s theme and features arcade games and pricey, sugary cocktails. You enter the back staff entrance through a vending machine door, and its best to make a reservation. Crowds are trendy and more Hollywood than K-Town.\r\n\r\n[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text css_animation=\"\"][templatera id=\"349\"][/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Break Room 86 at The Line Hotel','','publish','open','open','','thebreakroom86','','','2015-08-12 18:25:16','2015-08-13 01:25:16','',201,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?page_id=477',0,'page','',0),(480,3,'2015-06-03 23:42:04','2015-06-03 23:42:04','[vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]Its a little too easy to hate on The Line, with its roster of name-brand nightlife and dining, from the Houston Brothers new destination Break Room 86 to the hotels older, Roy Choi affiliated establishments, Pot and Commissary.\r\n\r\nPot is located in the Lines lobby and features a selection of dishes done in the celebrity chefs signature Korean-fusion street style. Though theres no kush served at the bar, there are a tasty variety of soju drinks and cocktails featuring kimchi and other Korean-inspired flavors for those seeking a zesty or out-of-the-ordinary buzz.\r\n\r\nWhile Pot clamors a bit for relevance, it clamors much more loudly on weekend nights, when the lobby fills with local young twenty-somethings forcing out the daytime crowd of bloggers and Ira Glass lookalikes. Our favorite time to stop by is right when the shift occurs, around 5:00 pm on a Friday, as music turns abruptly towards Top 40, cueing a mass exodus of bookish types. If you wait much longer, the comfy lobby starts to turn into the far right panel of a Hieronymus Bosch <a href=\"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/6d/The_Garden_of_Earthly_Delights_by_Bosch_High_Resolution.jpg/1280px-The_Garden_of_Earthly_Delights_by_Bosch_High_Resolution.jpg\">triptych</a>.\r\n\r\n<b>The Lowdown </b>\r\n\r\nPot is the Lines lobby bar and restaurant. Helmed by celeb-chef Roy Choi, it specializes in Korean-inspired food and cocktails, and goes from low-key coffee shop to packed nightclub in about an hour on weekends. <b></b>[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text css_animation=\"\"][templatera id=\"349\"][/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Pot at The Line Hotel','','publish','open','open','','eatatpot','','','2015-08-12 18:42:19','2015-08-13 01:42:19','',201,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?page_id=480',0,'page','',0),(483,3,'2015-06-03 23:51:55','2015-06-03 23:51:55','[vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]Roy Chois crown jewel, Commissary is located in the Line hotel, a modern Koreatown lounge with trendy, young crowds and a selection of swanky eating and drinking establishments. While Pot is closer to the street food Choi is most known for, Commissarys menu is inspired by local ingredients and rustic vegetable motifs drawn from its location on the bars rooftop greenhouse.\r\n\r\nDishes and drinks are identified not by name, but by botanical illustration-style images of their ingredients: a beet, a fish, a carrot. While more jaded Angelenos may find Chois pastoral imagery a little eyeroll-inducing, the drinks are delicious. We recommend the gin and juice special with beet or watermelon; cynics be warned though  it comes in a rough-and-tumble plastic tupperware that screams instagram me, and pick a really vintage looking filter!\r\n\r\nComplete with mismatched thrifted dishware, the most poorly imagined facet of Commisarys kitsch is its cramped, communal seating, which feels like a bit of a gip for the price tag  even if you like your food and drink on the scrappy side, a $15 cobb salad should get you more than a wobbly metal stool to sit on. We recommend reserving a table in advance, as otherwise you are likely to get stuck on the same side of a communal table as your date, knocking old-timey juice jars.\r\n\r\n<b>The Lowdown </b>\r\n\r\nCommissary is a quaint hotel restaurant and bar in the Line Hotels rooftop greenhouse. It has tasty gin, gimmicky digs and juice drinks but limited seating. Menus are by Roy Choi but service is a little lacking, despite the bars artisan flair.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text css_animation=\"\"][templatera id=\"349\"][/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Commissary at The Line Hotel','','publish','open','open','','commissary-at-the-line-hotel','','','2016-01-07 05:37:11','2016-01-07 13:37:11','',201,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?page_id=483',0,'page','',0),(485,3,'2015-06-03 23:56:01','2015-06-03 23:56:01','[vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]Koreatown is bizarrely full of nautical-themed establishments. Though the strangest and most unique of these is probably <a href=\"http://www.vice.com/en_ca/read/one-koreatown-psychic-loved-titanic-so-much-he-made-his-own-ship\">the Titanic-inspired Cafe Jack</a>, HMS Bounty is a more practical spot, even if its novelty isnt quite as over-the-top.\r\n\r\nThe Wilshire ship-themed dive is most acclaimed for its affordable cocktails and slightly seedy ambiance, both of which make it popular among budgeted locals, young punky types and boozy old-timers.\r\n\r\nOld and young drinkers alike gather at the Bounty to do what they do best  imbibe. The HMS Bounty is very much a drinkers bar but also serves food, though table service borders on nonexistent. If you can get served, the food menu is edible and fine for soaking up hard alcohol, but nothing to write home about: the Bountys simple sandwiches, burgers, and greasy bar fare are a step or two above the neighborhood Subway, but probably not much more than that.\r\n\r\nWith many tables and booths and a long communal bar area, the Bounty is a good choice for an intimate after-work drink with friends or a lively place not to spend the evening alone  its popular among casual daters because the ship theme and funny mixture of clientele provide plenty to talk about on otherwise awkward Tinder meetups. As drinks are dirt cheap, you wont have to wager your full paycheck on a potential love match.\r\n\r\n<b>The Lowdown</b>\r\n\r\nThe HMS Bounty, or The Bounty as its affectionately known, is a cutely seedy Koreatown dive with a ship motif, friendly patrons, and cheap cocktails. Its fun theme and affordability make it a good choice for dates, while the friendly, communal atmosphere also draws its fair share of singles mingling.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text css_animation=\"\"][templatera id=\"349\"][/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','The HMS Bounty','','publish','open','open','','thehmsbounty','','','2015-08-12 18:43:16','2015-08-13 01:43:16','',201,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?page_id=485',0,'page','',0),(487,3,'2015-06-03 23:59:25','2015-06-03 23:59:25','[vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]As locals know, Los Angeles Chinatown is a little more Disneyland than Polanski, decked out in kitschy pagodas and enclaves full of Spongebob childrens fair rides. (Yep, just accept it and move on). Next to these, though, lies General Lees, an upscale modern lounge whose ethos looks to the Far East.\r\n\r\nDrinks are quaintly themed craft cocktails, with names like Lost Orient Sour, East is East, and Old Chinatown. Though ingredients like green tea and sesame seed garnishes are promising, these can fall a little flat if youre looking to taste the booze  the signature drinks are attractive and cutely named but <i>very </i>sweet and a little hard to get buzzed off; if you dont have an intense sweet tooth, its difficult to drink more than one. At $12, they dont come cheaply either.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nWhat General Lees has going for it is its surroundings  set against the amorphous, ever changing landscape of DTLA, Chinatown nightlife is both novel and manageable: unlike most of Los Angeles, you get a definitive sense of where it begins and ends, and you can take a pretty comprehensive tour in a single night.\r\n\r\nEntertainment is one of General Lees greatest draws; the nightclub upstairs hosts shows and dancey DJ sets while the downstairs is lively, if sometimes annexed by quasi-private parties. Both areas have their own bars, and staff are quite nice and friendly, shielded from the stress and hellishness of more intense nightclubs. (General Lees is set off the main drag and surrounded by family restaurants and tourist shops.) If you get the chance, check out the nearby Poetic Research Bureau, a library and reading space that holds readings and events for local artists and writers.\r\n\r\nDress is casual and covers are cheap or nonexistent. (Often, there will be a $10-20 cover for an upstairs show but all are welcome to drink downstairs and listen to a house DJ.) There is no smoking area per se, but re-entry is easy: smokers tend to gravitate toward the nearby childrens amusement park rides.\r\n\r\n<b>The Lowdown </b>\r\n\r\nGeneral Lees is a Chinatown bar and venue with friendly bartenders and pricey themed cocktails. Most of its charm lies in its location in the quaint DTLA-adjacent neighborhood. If you get the chance, wander around the local area, snag some wasabi-ginger lays, grab a bite at Chugo or check out a reading at the Poetic Research Bureau.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text css_animation=\"\"][templatera id=\"349\"][/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','General Lee\'s','','publish','open','open','','general-lees','','','2016-01-07 05:39:32','2016-01-07 13:39:32','',201,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?page_id=487',0,'page','',0),(489,3,'2015-06-04 00:02:45','2015-06-04 00:02:45','[vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]R Bar is the kind of place you can drive by a thousand times without ever grokking that there might be a venue there  which is a good thing. Its covert location and password policy shield it from the kind of raucous foot traffic that permeates pedestrian areas (though LA doesnt have many of these).\r\n\r\nThe cozy bar has a fair amount of seating, mostly divided up into private booths separated with curtains and adorned with lush, brocade fabrics. House drinks are tasty, but can run steep for the East side. There is always a drink special, though, and if you are willing to spend a little more, we recommend the 3331, a tequila drink with tamarind which pairs well with some of the nearby snacks: 8th houses some of Los Angeles best taco trucks, while the bars kitchen also serves its own selection of greasy fare and guilty pleasures: feta fries, grilled cheese, wings, quesadillas, and more.\r\n\r\nR Bars biggest draw is its karaoke nights, hosted by much-loved emcee FUN DMC. These take place every Sunday and Wednesday. Theres never a cover and regulars can have pretty intimidating pipes, but its also a supportive and fun place to belt out 80s hits or R&amp;B if you arent vocally gifted. While theres no smoking area per se, people gather outside smoking and complimenting each other\'s songs  all of this lends itself to a sense of a scene that isnt always easy to find in Los Angeles, where bar crowds often vary greatly by night. R Bar is more reminiscent of Williamsburg or Austin.\r\n\r\nPasswords are available on the R Bar Facebook page and usually stay the same for a week or so. The bouncers and bartenders are very helpful and friendly. (I have left my wallet or phone there more than once and panicked, only to find that it was quickly scooped up by an attentive member of the R Bar staff  so its a good place for absentminded drinkers like myself). Seating can be challenging on karaoke nights, so arrive early if youre set on a table, and Uber  theres almost never street parking.\r\n\r\nWhile the secret spots classy furnishings, low-key parlor atmosphere, and password policy invoke spots like No Vacancy or Dirty Laundry, the vibe is distinctly more casual than aesthetically similar Hollywood bars. Theres no dress code, and most patrons live in the neighborhood.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nR Bars biggest drawback is its price tag, which is deceptively high for its locale. If you can spend a little, however, its a great place to go for karaoke or an offbeat after-work drink on the other side of Hollywood.\r\n\r\n<b>The Lowdown </b>\r\n\r\nR Bar is a Koreatown speakeasy with a password policy and a vibrant karaoke scene. There are also trivia and other theme nights, which can be found on the bars Facebook page along with its current password and pertinent drink specials.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text css_animation=\"\"][templatera id=\"349\"][/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','R Bar','','publish','open','open','','rbarktown','','','2015-08-12 18:42:37','2015-08-13 01:42:37','',201,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?page_id=489',0,'page','',0),(491,3,'2015-06-04 00:06:41','2015-06-04 00:06:41','[vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]Jewels Catch One was LAs first black-owned gay club, and is also widely hailed as Californias longest-running industrial music club. The bar is known to many as the host of goth night Das Bunker, but the venue also hosts other genres like techno, house, and ambient electronic.\r\n\r\nAlso known as the Catch One nightclub, it lies a little off the map, on Pico Blvd. in Arlington Heights, but in close range of K-Town and DTLA.\r\n\r\nThe club holds two bars: downstairs, there is a roomy dive with a small stage and decks, while the upper floor opens up for later, bigger, wilder parties, and boasts a massive neon sign reading DISCO. Typically, the upstairs area is reserved for late, lively DJ sets, while the downstairs stage hosts more ambient electronic acts and occasional instrumental sets. There is also a roomy downstairs gazebo for smokers, but the bar enforces a strict no-drinks-outside policy.\r\n\r\nThe lower floor has red-tinted, low lighting  spatially, it looks similar to the bar that characters Jackie Brown and Max Cherry visited in Quentin Tarentinos 1997 film.\r\n\r\nBecause of its remote location, its best to come prepared with cash for the door, as most nights charge cover, and finding an ATM nearby can prove challenging.\r\n\r\nEntrance tends to be relatively pricey, especially later on in the night, so its not a great place to stumble into and best to visit for specific shows and DJ sets. Drinks are reasonably priced, but nothing special  keep it simple. Though the club is open until 4am  a rarity in Los Angeles  they stop serving at 2am.\r\n\r\nCatch One has lots of space to dance, and sound quality is good, while dress is casual  anything goes.\r\n\r\nSecurity is relatively tight, though, and can be a little pushy  they arent afraid to kick people out or check thoroughly for illicit party favors if you seem to be lingering in the bathroom.\r\n\r\nOn the bright side, you <i>can </i>enjoy as much fried chicken as you want from the grill next to the smoking area.\r\n\r\nSadly, Catch One will be closing by the end of Summer 2015, leaving just a few months to hit the dance floor one last time.\r\n\r\n<b>The Lowdown</b>\r\n\r\nJewels Catch One is a multi-level nightclub with a diverse roster of events, but is most known for hosting goth/industrial club night Das Bunker. The surrounding area is vaguely desolate and a tad seedy, but parties are fun and a nice change from the Hollywood club scene.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text css_animation=\"\"][templatera id=\"349\"][/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Jewels Catch One','','publish','open','open','','jewels-catch-one','','','2015-08-12 18:41:16','2015-08-13 01:41:16','',201,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?page_id=491',0,'page','',0),(494,3,'2015-06-04 00:12:19','2015-06-04 00:12:19','[vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]Inconspicuously tucked away in a Thai Town / Los Feliz strip mall on Hollywood Boulevard, Jumbo\'s Clown Room is a great place to grab a cheap, strong drink and watch a few dances.\r\n\r\nEach dancer gets to pick her own songs, so the clubs esoteric entertainment not only shows off impressive acrobatic feats, but gives a uniquely strong sense of the personalities of Jumbos talented performers; last time I stopped by, selections included everything from top 40 to Stevie Nicks Gypsy and the Smiths.\r\n\r\nJumbos crowds are relatively equal parts men and women, and the atmosphere is respectful  tips are appreciated and expected. Dance styles are an imaginative hybrid of strip and burlesque, but vary depending on night, song and performer.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nAs many misinformed Yelpers have disparaged, Jumbo\'s is not a strip club or a conventionally styled Hollywood bikini bar  if you are seeking nudity, go elsewhere.\r\n\r\nAtmosphere is low-key and quaintly seedy, but like most dives, space is limited, especially for big parties hoping to be seated as groups. What Jumbo\'s might lack in nipple, it makes up for in exciting Hollywood history  the bar has been around since the 70s and has appeared in footage by Penn &amp; Teller and been featured in a Third Eye Blind video. In the 90s, Courtney Love was a Jumbo\'s dancer.\r\n\r\nAs parking is limited, it is wise to Uber or Lyft. Though there is a bouncer, there arent door fees or dress codes  unless you are falling down, belligerent, or terribly rude, getting in isnt a problem. Jumbos is a particularly fun place to stop by towards the end of a night out, and is typically at its busiest from midnight to 2am.\r\n\r\nBring plenty of singles for tipping dancers and bar staff, who also tend to be a bit curt. (Who can blame them? Dance bars always attract more than their fair share of sloppy, drunk jerks.)\r\n\r\nDespite this, crowds tend to be young, hip and respectful, and more into Jumbos sensual retro ambiance than the promise of a nip-slip.\r\n\r\n<b>The Lowdown </b>\r\n\r\nJumbos Clown Room is a divey dance bar known for its close quarters, understated vibe, and most of all, its myriad talented acrobats. Thankfully, there are no clowns.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text css_animation=\"\"][templatera id=\"349\"][/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Jumbo\'s Clown Room','','publish','open','open','','jumbosclownroom','','','2015-08-12 18:41:26','2015-08-13 01:41:26','',201,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?page_id=494',0,'page','',0),(496,3,'2015-06-04 00:33:17','2015-06-04 00:33:17','[vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]Los Felizs Harvard &amp; Stone is as quaint as its surrounding village, complete with retro-chic dcor, carefully crafted old-style cocktails, and a rustic, refurbished wood interior.\r\n\r\nChanneling Southern nostalgia, the bar feels about as close to Nashville or Austin as youll get in Los Angeles.\r\n\r\nDcor harkens back to Western saloons, and commits fully to the delightfully twangy ambiance with a house band playing blues, rock n roll, bluegrass, and Americana. Some nights also include burlesque performances, while later on, the music gets more upbeat and dancey, though remains on the nostalgic side of nightlife: more Footloose than Young Money.\r\n\r\nIn keeping with the boho-country theme, bartenders don suspenders and fedoras, and antique lighting and furniture finish off the look. Patrons are also encouraged to dress to theme: shorts, sports gear, logos, flip-flops, loud colors, and of course <i>shiny shirts </i>are discouraged.\r\n\r\nThere is a railroad-apartment-style narrow smoking area on the lower floor, while the second floor, a favorite hangout of regulars, also has its own smoking patio.\r\n\r\nThough we love the live band at the Friday and Saturday burlesque shows, the bar also draws a healthy weekday crowd with a lateish 8 - 9:30pm happy hour offering five-dollar old fashioneds, though bar manager and expert mixologist Serena Herrick prefers to sip some sherry<a href=\"http://www.lamag.com/liquidlablog/shift-drink-serena-herrick-harvard-stone/?fb_action_ids=10153113592220726&amp;fb_action_types=og.shares\"> after her shift</a>, telling Los Angeles Magazine she prefers something a little more chill and something lower-proof than the occasional shot I have here and there throughout the night.\r\n\r\nThe menu changes seasonally, but always provides a wide selection of interesting (and creatively named) drinks and ingredients: favorites include the Fat Guy in a Little Coat, Tonic the Hedgehog, and The Racks on Racks on Racks.\r\n\r\nCrowds tend to be mostly 20s and 30s. While the bar is a great place to meet people, its also a favorite spot to host birthdays or other parties, or sip a drink from one of the vintage leather couches.\r\n\r\nDesigned and operated by the Houston Brothers (No Vacancy / Dirty Laundry / Good Times at Davey Waynes), Harvard &amp; Stones country western ambiance is more sophisticated than it is hokey  deliciously quirky cocktails and performances will make everyone game for a ho-down, though its best to cab over  Los Feliz parking can be a bit of an ordeal.\r\n\r\n<b>The Lowdown</b>\r\n\r\nHarvard &amp; Stone is a trendy, saloon-style bar with live performances and a talented staff of dapper mixologists. Crowds are biggest on weekend nights, when the bars live band accompanies burlesque performances.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text css_animation=\"\"][templatera id=\"349\"][/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Harvard & Stone','','publish','open','open','','harvard-stone','','','2015-08-12 18:44:38','2015-08-13 01:44:38','',201,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?page_id=496',0,'page','',0),(498,3,'2015-06-04 00:46:28','2015-06-04 00:46:28','[vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]Offering mismatched retro furnishings and a wide selection of games, the Spare Room might be deemed the kooky aunt of the Roosevelts family of drinking establishments.\r\n\r\nLocated on the hotels second floor mezzanine directly above Library Bar, the venue is a haven of kitsch for those who want their drinks classy and poured with a side of nostalgia. Handcrafted surfaces, lush dcor, and luxury furnishings portray a timeless, vintage feel throughout the modern hotels swanky-quaint second floor cocktail outpost.\r\n\r\nThe Spare Rooms menu displays a mantra from Plato, declaring You can tell more about a person in an hour of play, than you can in a year of conversation while the venues website neatly sums up its hybrid of old and new Hollywood with lines from George Bernard Shaw:\r\n\r\n<i>We don\'t stop playing because we grow old;</i>\r\n\r\n<i>We grow old because we stop playing.</i>\r\n\r\nIn keeping with the motif, The Spare Room hosts board-game-themed parties in its cozy cocktail lounge, providing house sets of dominoes, Jenga, Monopoly, Connect Four, Battleship, and Checkers, while groups are encouraged to reserve a lane in the adjoining bowling alley for $100 an hour.\r\n\r\nThe punnily-named Spare Room isnt your average bowling alley, though  you wont find any nacho cheese, seedy dcor or rinky-dink lighting fixtures. Instead, the bar and adjoining lanes are elegantly designed and luxuriously decorated with attention to lush detailing.\r\n\r\nStrikes and spares are scored on an old-style blackboard, and guests are encouraged to rent hand-cobbled shoes to go with the sleek 20s architecture. Waitresses sport vintage dresses  la Jordan Baker, echoing the period theme, while wood bureaus and brass railings lend a modicum of class to even the most clumsily directed gutter balls.\r\n\r\nWith a DJ booth converted from an antique vanity and old timey knick-knacks dispersed around, the Spare Rooms authenticity is far more chic than it is shabby. The menu offers a large selection of wittily titled craft cocktails and pop-culture references, from the Eternal Sunshine to the tequila-based Hooked On a Feeling. For cinephiles, we recommend the You Drink Our Milkshake: a cocktail of Absolut, Coffee Heering, dark crme de cacao, cream, and lemon essence that nods to the brutal bowling-alley scene in Paul Thomas Andersons There Will Be Blood, which inspired the Spare Rooms lanes layout.\r\n\r\nThough crowds tend to be young and hip, the bars plush comforts, carefully curated dcor and velvet drapery also make it a favorite of local architects. If you arent feeling particularly playful or nostalgic, some nights also feature DJ sets and dance parties and/or other live music performances.\r\n\r\n<b>The Lowdown</b>\r\n\r\nThe Spare Room is a classy Hollywood cocktail lounge with board games and bowling alleys. Located on the second floor of the Roosevelt Hotel, the picturesque space is particularly good for groups and small private parties.\r\n\r\n[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text css_animation=\"\"][templatera id=\"349\"][/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Spare Room Bar at The Roosevelt Hotel','','publish','open','open','','spare-room-bar-the-roosevelt-hotel','','','2015-08-12 18:43:04','2015-08-13 01:43:04','',201,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?page_id=498',0,'page','',0),(500,3,'2015-06-04 00:51:05','2015-06-04 00:51:05','[vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]Tucked away in the lobby of Hollywoods Roosevelt hotel, Library Bar is a haven for bookish boozers and New York expats. The space draws inspiration from private English libraries, with leather couches, cowhide rugs, and stacks of classics.\r\n\r\nTrue to its name, the venue has just as much reading material as it does drinking options; its dark mahogany shelves are filled with classics from Henry Miller to Hans Christian Anderson.\r\n\r\nBartenders Matt Biancaniello and Chris Hewes craft the ever-changing roster of fresh, inventive cocktail recipes based on what\'s available at the local farmers market.\r\n\r\nWhile youre allowed to order off the menu, the real draw of Library Bar is its omakase-style service  we recommend letting the staff create a drink to suit your palate.\r\n\r\nThe bar is a popular spot for those hoping to escape rowdy Hollywood nightlife and typical hotel bars, so scoring a spot in one of Library Bars coveted cozy nooks and crannies can prove a little difficult.\r\n\r\n<b>The Lowdown</b>\r\n\r\nLibrary Bar is a cozy den in the Roosevelt Hotel with a menu of tasty classic cocktails and shelves of literary classics.\r\n\r\n[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text css_animation=\"\"][templatera id=\"349\"][/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Library Bar at The Roosevelt Hotel','','publish','open','open','','library-bar-at-the-roosevelt-hotel','','','2015-08-12 18:41:38','2015-08-13 01:41:38','',201,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?page_id=500',0,'page','',0),(503,1,'2015-06-04 02:09:10','2015-06-04 02:09:10','','Order &ndash; June 4, 2015 @ 02:09 AM','','wc-processing','open','closed','order_556fb3035dd63','order-jun-04-2015-0208-am','','','2015-06-04 02:09:10','2015-06-04 02:09:10','',0,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?post_type=shop_order&#038;p=503',0,'shop_order','',3),(504,1,'2015-06-04 03:48:48','2015-06-04 03:48:48','','Order &ndash; June 4, 2015 @ 03:48 AM','','wc-processing','open','closed','order_556fca9ddb860','order-jun-04-2015-0348-am','','','2015-06-04 03:48:48','2015-06-04 03:48:48','',0,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?post_type=shop_order&#038;p=504',0,'shop_order','',3),(505,1,'2015-06-04 03:53:39','2015-06-04 03:53:39','','Order &ndash; June 4, 2015 @ 03:53 AM','','wc-processing','open','closed','order_556fcb818a4d3','order-jun-04-2015-0352-am','','','2015-06-04 03:53:39','2015-06-04 03:53:39','',0,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?post_type=shop_order&#038;p=505',0,'shop_order','',3),(506,1,'2015-06-04 03:58:47','2015-06-04 03:58:47','','Order &ndash; June 4, 2015 @ 03:58 AM','','wc-processing','open','closed','order_556fccf4d746c','order-jun-04-2015-0358-am','','','2015-06-04 03:58:47','2015-06-04 03:58:47','',0,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?post_type=shop_order&#038;p=506',0,'shop_order','',3),(507,1,'2015-06-04 06:36:12','2015-06-04 06:36:12','','Order &ndash; June 4, 2015 @ 06:36 AM','','wc-processing','open','closed','order_556ff1d8d3057','order-jun-04-2015-0636-am','','','2015-06-04 06:36:12','2015-06-04 06:36:12','',0,'http://walkthenight.wpengine.com/la/?post_type=shop_order&#038;p=507',0,'shop_order','',3),(508,3,'2015-06-04 17:34:07','2015-06-04 17:34:07','[vc_row full_width=\"\" parallax=\"\" parallax_image=\"\"][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text]Dirty Laundry is a lively former speakeasy coyly hidden beneath a Hollywood apartment building. A neon sign reading SEX lies just behind the entrance, if you can find it  while the bars name is a nod to a Prohibition-era method of sneaking booze in a laundry basket.\r\n\r\nThe dimly lit club is best known for its inventive drinks and jazz-age vibes  bartenders sport a uniform of black jeans, fitted white tees and thin black suspenders, while the dress code warns patrons that shiny shirts, baseball caps, tennis shoes and flip flops will not be permitted to enter the premises.\r\n\r\nMixology is top-notch, offering Pop-Rocks-garnished mint juleps and other kooky twists on Prohibition-era drinks like the High Desert, a sazerac rinsed with absinthe and set aflame. Crowd favorites include rye whiskey and kaffir-lime infused vodka, but all the house cocktails boast bizarre and festive ingredients like aloe vera and cactus pear. Signature drinks are $12, but are generously poured, tasty, and easy on the eyes. Dirty Laundry also offers dressed-up boozy punches aimed at large groups and private parties.\r\n\r\nMusic aims primarily to keep the crowd dancing, with DJs playing a fresh mix of jazz, hip hop, disco and 80s hits. Those seeking a space to cozy up or chat should reserve a seat in the Valentino Room, named after silent film actor and former owner Rudolph Valentino, and initially slated to house a Prohibition-era distillery that was never fully actualized. Now, the space hosts Dirty Laundrys most intimate environs, and offers a quiet, atmospheric refuge from disco, dance, and other bar revelry. Elegant banquettes and even its own private bar hidden behind a fake bookshelf round out the vibe.\r\n\r\nDirty Laundry is helmed by the Houston Brothers, who are responsible for local favorites No Vacancy and La Descarga, and new disco hotspot Good Times at Davey Waynes. In keeping with its speakeasy theme, the bar is password-protected, but getting in isnt too difficult, provided youre sober enough to check the @DirtyLaundryBar Twitter feed. Still, drink lines do happen, so we recommend scurrying your gams over a bit early if you wanna snag a seat. Thats the crop!\r\n\r\n<b>The Lowdown</b>\r\n\r\nDirty Laundry was once a silent film actors Prohibition-era speakeasy, but has been since resuscitated as a trendy, exclusive nightclub. The bar is password-protected, encourages semi-formal dress, and offers a menu of delicious, creative cocktails. Private parties are well accounted for, and the Valentino Room offers an intimate club experience to smaller groups on any night  provided youve made a reservation.[/vc_column_text][/vc_column][vc_column width=\"1/2\"][vc_column_text css_animation=\"\"][templatera id=\"349\"][/vc_column_text][/vc_column][/vc_row]','Dirty Laundry','','publish','open','open','','dirtylaundrybar','','','2015-08-12 18:29:41','2015-08-13 01:29:41','',201,'